  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a lived reality for many who've seen their potential dimmed by the very labels society assigns them. As a retired man who grew up in Washington DC with a father who had a bachelor's degree and a mother who only went to primary school, I've seen how education can both empower and burden depending on the context. Back in my day, when I was a young man in the 1940s, the idea of a girl in engineering or a person of color in physics was almost unthinkable. Today, we're still grappling with the same invisible weight—when someone from a group historically underrepresented in STEM fields is told they're not 'meant' for these fields, their performance suffers. I've always believed that addressing stereotype threat isn't about changing the system overnight but about creating spaces where every individual feels they belong. It's about recognizing that when a student from a low-income background is told they're 'not smart enough' for math, that message can linger long after the class ends. In my creative mind, I see solutions like mentorship programs that pair students with role models who've navigated similar challenges, or simply having conversations in classrooms that normalize diverse perspectives. But it's not just about programs—it's about the everyday interactions that reinforce or dismantle those stereotypes. I've traveled the world and seen how different cultures approach education, and I've found that when people feel heard and valued, they perform better. So yes, we absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM—it's a matter of fairness, of ensuring that talent isn't wasted because of a label someone was born with. It's time to build bridges, not walls.",
